{{short description|negative attitudes and discrimination toward  vegetarian and vegan people}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}
{{Discrimination sidebar|expanded=Social}}
'''Vegaphobia''' is an aversion to [[vegetarian]] and [[vegan]] people.<ref name="cole">{{cite journal|title=Vegaphobia: derogatory discourses of veganism and the reproduction of speciesism in UK national newspapers|first1=Matthew|last1=Cole|first2=Karen|last2=Morgan|date=1 March 2011|journal=The British Journal of Sociology|volume=62|issue=1|pages=134–153|doi=10.1111/j.1468-4446.2010.01348.x|pmid = 21361905}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ar-conference.org/2013/details.php?id=44|title=Vegephobia, what is it? Why is it important to fight it? (Jola Cora) [IARC2013]|author=|date=|website=ar-conference.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z70tDwAAQBAJ&q=Vegaphobia&pg=PA120|title=Understanding Veganism: Biography and Identity|last=Griffin|first=Nathan Stephens|date=2017-07-20|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319521022|location=|pages=24, 47, 120|language=en}}</ref><ref>Jones, R. C: (2016) Veganisms. In Castricano, J. & Simonsen, R. R. ''Critical Perspectives on Veganism''. Palgrave Macmillan. p. 25</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-07/why-do-vegans-have-such-bad-reputations/10468652|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Why do vegans have such bad reputations?|first=Tani|last=Khara|date=November 7, 2018|access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=vice>{{cite web|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/vbabp9/theres-a-term-for-hating-on-vegans-and-its-vegaphobia|title=There's a Term For Hating On Vegans And It's Vegaphobia|access-date=July 20, 2019|date=November 26, 2018|first=Manisha|last=Krishnan}}</ref>{{Excessive citations inline|date=October 2019}} It is in the 21st century that it began to frame the phenomenon in the sociological sphere and makes its appearance "vegaphobia". In 2007, a survey called "Vegaphobia: disproportionate talk about [[veganism]] in British national newspapers" took place in the United Kingdom, which examined 397 articles containing the terms "vegan", "vegans" and "veganism". The researchers found that 74.3% of the items are classified as "negatives"; 20.2% "neutral" and only 5.5% "positive". Negative items were in order of frequency: ridiculing veganism; characterize veganism as [[asceticism]]; affirming that veganism is difficult or impossible to sustain; describe veganism as a fashion; portray vegans as sentimentalists; defining vegans as hostile.<ref name="cole" />

[[Laura Wright (academic)|Laura Wright]] claims that media organisations and wider discourse routinely mischaracterise vegan diets<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Vegan Studies Project : Food, Animals, and Gender in the Age of Terror|last=Wright|first=Laura|publisher=University of Georgia Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=EBSCOhost|pages=}}</ref> and highlights situations where media outlets report the death of children from a 'vegan diet' rather than the neglect that was the actual cause.<ref name="Wright2015">{{cite book|author=Laura Wright|title=The Vegan Studies Project: Food, Animals, and Gender in the Age of Terror|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gwPaCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA89|date=1 October 2015|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-4854-4|pages=89–}}</ref> However, Christophe Traïni writes that some vegan activists may present themselves "as members of an oppressed minority rebelling against 'vegephobia{{'"}}.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.cairn-int.info/article-E_RFSP_624_0559--between-disgust-and-moral-indignation.htm|title=Between disgust and moral indignation|first1=Christophe|last1=Traïni|first2=Katharine|last2=Throssell|date=|via=cairn-int.info|journal=Revue Française de Science Politique|volume=62|issue=4}}</ref>

However, the application of the term "vegaphobia"—and the extent to which it can be compared to other forms of discrimination—remains a divisive issue,<ref name=vice/> with Sophie Wilkinson of [[Grazia]] opining that "...discrimination is about being treated differently for who you are, not for what you choose to do." and that discrimination against vegans (unlike [[sexism]], [[racism]], [[homophobia]], etc.) doesn't tend to go beyond the level of [[microaggression]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://graziadaily.co.uk/life/food-and-drink/no-vegan-based-discrimination-is-nonsense/|publisher=[[Grazia]]|title=No, Vegan-Based Discrimination Is Nonsense|first=Sophie|last=Wilkinson|date=December 3, 2018|access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref>

At the 2013 International Animal Rights Conference, actress and producer Jola Cora, discussed the topic in a presentation called "Vegaphobia, what is it?"<ref name="youtube1">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tucw3cCzjLc|title=Vegephobia, what is it? Jola Cora at IARC 2013 Luxembourg|last=VeganKanal|date=12 September 2013|via=YouTube}}</ref>

In 2018, a survey of British and American vegans from the weight-loss application Lifesum found eight out of ten respondents to have experienced some form of anti-vegan prejudice.<ref name=vice/> 

